## Objective

Introduce the `.convention` context file type to document enforceable standards across the framework, starting with commit message conventions.

## Task Context

- Current state: 
  - Framework has `.task`, `.plan`, `.report`, `.template` context files
  - No standardized way to document conventions
  - Git slice created but empty
  
- Desired state:
  - `.convention` files documented as a context file type
  - `Commit.convention` provides clear commit message standards
  - Workspace treats `.convention` as markdown
  - Convention files referenced in delegation workflows

## Task Deliverables

- D1: `Git/Commit.convention` - Conventional commit specification with types, scopes, format rules
- D2: `Planning/ContextFiles.md` - Updated with `.convention` section describing purpose, schema, location
- D3: `.code-workspace` - File associations updated to include `*.convention`

## Architecture Decisions

- AD-1: Use Conventional Commits 1.0.0 as the standard — Rationale: Industry standard, tool support, semantic versioning compatible
- AD-2: Place convention files in relevant slices — Rationale: Vertical slice architecture keeps conventions close to related code/prompts
- AD-3: Convention files are prescriptive, not descriptive — Rationale: Clear enforcement rules for agents and developers

## Success Criteria

- [ ] Markdown linting passes on all new files
- [ ] `.convention` type documented with clear schema and examples
- [ ] `Commit.convention` is comprehensive and actionable
- [ ] Workspace settings include `.convention` file association

